  { question: "How do I calculate screen width and height from diagonal?", answer: "Use the diagonal measurement and aspect ratio. The formula is: height = diagonal / sqrt((aspect_width/aspect_height)^2 + 1), then width = height x (aspect_width/aspect_height). For a 27-inch 16:9 display, the height is about 13.2 inches and the width is about 23.5 inches." },
  { question: "What is PPI and why does it matter?", answer: "PPI (Pixels Per Inch) measures pixel density. Higher PPI means sharper, more detailed images. Calculate it by dividing the diagonal resolution (sqrt of horizontal^2 + vertical^2) by the diagonal screen size. A 27-inch 4K (3840x2160) display has about 163 PPI, while the same resolution on a 32-inch screen drops to about 138 PPI." },
  { question: "What aspect ratio do most monitors use?", answer: "Most modern monitors use 16:9 (widescreen), which is the standard for HD (1920x1080), QHD (2560x1440), and 4K (3840x2160) resolutions. Ultrawide monitors use 21:9 or 32:9. Older monitors used 4:3 or 5:4. Apple displays use 16:10. Choosing the right aspect ratio depends on your use case: 16:9 for general use, ultrawide for productivity and gaming." },
