    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Screen Size Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter the diagonal screen size in inches (found in the product specifications or measured corner to corner). Set the aspect ratio using two numbers, such as 16 and 9 for a standard widescreen display. Optionally, enter the horizontal and vertical resolution in pixels to calculate PPI (pixels per inch). The calculator instantly computes the physical width, height, viewable area, and pixel density.
      </p>
      <p>
        Common aspect ratios include 16:9 (standard widescreen), 16:10 (common in laptops), 4:3 (legacy monitors), 21:9 (ultrawide), and 32:9 (super ultrawide). If you are unsure of the aspect ratio, divide the horizontal resolution by the vertical resolution and look for the closest standard ratio.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Screen Dimensions and Pixel Density</h2>
      <p>
        A screen's diagonal measurement does not directly tell you its width and height because these depend on the aspect ratio. A 27-inch 16:9 screen is about 23.5 inches wide and 13.2 inches tall, while a 27-inch 4:3 screen would be 21.6 inches wide and 16.2 inches tall. The same diagonal size can produce very different usable areas depending on the aspect ratio, with wider ratios having less area per diagonal inch.
      </p>

      <h3>Why PPI Matters</h3>
      <p>
        Pixel density determines how sharp text and images appear. At typical desktop viewing distances (2-3 feet), a PPI of 90-110 is standard for most users. Higher PPI (140+) provides noticeably sharper text, beneficial for reading and detail work. Apple's Retina displays aim for PPI high enough that individual pixels are indistinguishable at normal viewing distances. For the same resolution, a smaller screen has higher PPI and thus sharper image quality.
      </p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Screen Size</h3>
      <p>
        For general office work and web browsing, 24-27 inches at 1080p or 1440p is the sweet spot. Content creators and professionals benefit from 27-32 inches at 4K resolution. Gamers often prefer 24-27 inches for competitive play (faster scanning) or 32+ inches and ultrawide for immersive experiences. Consider your desk depth and viewing distance: a 32-inch monitor may be too large if you sit only 2 feet away, as you will need to turn your head to see the edges.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I calculate screen width and height from diagonal?</h3>
      <p>
        Use the diagonal measurement and aspect ratio. The formula is: height = diagonal / sqrt((aspect_width/aspect_height)^2 + 1), then width = height x (aspect_width/aspect_height). For a 27-inch 16:9 display, the height is about 13.2 inches and the width is about 23.5 inches.
      </p>

      <h3>What is PPI and why does it matter?</h3>
      <p>
        PPI (Pixels Per Inch) measures pixel density. Higher PPI means sharper, more detailed images. Calculate it by dividing the diagonal resolution by the diagonal screen size. A 27-inch 4K display has about 163 PPI, while the same resolution on a 32-inch screen drops to about 138 PPI.
      </p>

      <h3>What aspect ratio do most monitors use?</h3>
      <p>
        Most modern monitors use 16:9 (widescreen), which is the standard for HD, QHD, and 4K resolutions. Ultrawide monitors use 21:9 or 32:9. Older monitors used 4:3 or 5:4. Apple displays use 16:10.
      </p>

      <h3>Is a bigger screen always better?</h3>
      <p>
        Not necessarily. Screen size should match your viewing distance and use case. For desktop use at 2-3 feet, 24-27 inches is ideal for most people. Larger screens benefit from higher resolutions to maintain good pixel density.
      </p>

      <h3>How much bigger is a 32-inch screen compared to 27-inch?</h3>
      <p>
        Screen area scales with the square of the diagonal. A 32-inch 16:9 screen has about 437 square inches, while a 27-inch has about 311 square inches. That means a 32-inch screen is about 40% larger in area, despite being only 19% larger diagonally.
      </p>


